  "statement": "# Min Cost to Connect All Points\n\nConnect all points with minimum total Manhattan distance.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: points = [[0,0],[2,2],[3,10],[5,2],[7,0]]\nOutput: 20\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: points = [[3,12],[-2,5],[-4,1]]\nOutput: 18\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: points = [[0,0]]\nOutput: 0\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return values follow the method description.",
  "editorial": "Use the graph structure directly: traverse reachable states, maintain visited or distance state, and update the answer when each node or cell is settled.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minCostConnectPoints(self, points):\n        n = len(points)\n        used = [False] * n\n        best = [float('inf')] * n\n        best[0] = 0\n        total = 0\n        for _ in range(n):\n            pick = min((i for i in range(n) if not used[i]), key=lambda i: best[i])\n            used[pick] = True; total += best[pick]\n            x, y = points[pick]\n            for i, (a, b) in enumerate(points):\n                if not used[i]:\n                    best[i] = min(best[i], abs(x - a) + abs(y - b))\n        return total\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Model the state explicitly.",
    "Prefer linear or near-linear graph traversal when possible."
  ],
